The "Green Deal" in Europe
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The "Green Deal for Europe" announced by the European Commission is to date the first global sustainable development plan decided by a major region on the planet.
It thus becomes a benchmark for the entire world – a guide for the transformation towards a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, a first agenda for all to achieve this.
Of course, the task ahead for Europeans is daunting.
Even reading the documents that have just been made public is like that: an abundance at first glance of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of involved and related topics ranging from energy to transportation, from food to industry.
Its critics will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense: it is rational.
The sustainable development objectives are clearly stated, targets are defined according to goals subject to a timeline, and programs and procedures are adapted to these targets.
In total, the stated ambition is to achieve carbon neutrality (net zero greenhouse gas emissions) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that ends destructive plastic and petrochemical pollution, pesticide and toxic waste pollution, to set up a "farm-to-table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed industrial products, nor the earth with unsustainable farming practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on citizens themselves.
Again, critics will view the announcements of public consultations as mere empty rhetoric.
But try telling them about useless chatter to President French Emmanuel Macron, who has been facing protests turning violent for over a year, or to President Chilean Sebastián Piñera, whose country erupted in unrest this autumn following a slight increase in metro ticket prices.
Both Macron and Piñera are convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to carbon neutrality in their countries by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to organize or structure a public consultation, but after the fact.
American neo-liberals will once again mock and assert that the "market" will know how to remedy climate change.
But just look at today's United States.
If neo-liberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have reason to be concerned.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means dealing with broken elevators, malfunctioning escalators, stalled shuttle buses, taxis that don't arrive, non-existent train connections, highways in such poor condition that they cannot be driven, replaced by detours.
The reason for these malfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each American election cycle costs around 8 billion dollars, if not more, and the funding comes from billionaires, major oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobbying group, and interest groups determined to lower taxes and protect the status quo at all costs.
Market solutions become a farce when politics is subjected to all the influences that emanate from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Deal shows what a government should be like, rather than one subordinate to corporate interests.
The European Green Deal actually demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense, not narrowly partisan).
A mixed economy, combining markets, state regulatory power, public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it is the most sophisticated industrial policy at its highest level.
(I recently outlined, in broad terms, what such a social-democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that advanced technologies, which will allow the creation of an advanced decarbonized, resource-efficient, and thus ecologically sustainable economy, exist at either the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and collaborative economics in transportation or other infrastructure, we can decarbonize the energy system, transition to a circular economy, and drastically reduce primary resource flows.
But this requires overcoming three major challenges.
The first is to overcome interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
Major oil companies will need to absorb losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation in the form of income support, retraining, and other public aids.
The European plan rightly claims a “just transition.”
The second challenge is financing.
Europe, as of course other world regions, will need to redirect a relatively small portion of its production, around 1% to 2%, towards the green economy, particularly for new infrastructure, public markets, research and development, industrial equipment renewal, etc. Funding will come from the private sector but also from public budgets.
Europe must stand up to ideologues who oppose increases in EU spending.
The facts must be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
Europe represents about 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China accounts for 30% and the United States for 14%.
Even if Europe successfully implements its green pact in full, it will be futile if other world regions do not join in the fight.
European leaders therefore rightly consider that diplomacy is fundamental to the success of the green pact.
Let's take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest CO2 emitter (although its per capita emissions remain half those of the United States).
China alone will determine the future of global climate.
On one hand, Chinese leaders know their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it does not make sufficient efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must confront the dangers of the unintended cold war launched by America.
Hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist decarbonization, especially since Trump himself rejects it, under pressure from the United States.
European diplomacy could make a difference if it refuses to succumb to America’s covert measures to hinder China and instead offers China a clear and positive partnership: working together to establish sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal similar to Europe’s.
Such a partnership would be immensely beneficial for Europe, China, and the dozen or so Eurasian countries that separate them, not to mention the world as a whole.
The European Union has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
